WEBVTT

STYLE
::cue(c.color9CD5FF) { color: #9CD5FF; }
::cue(c.colora8c7fa) { color: #a8c7fa; }

1
00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:07.000 line:5% align:center
<b><c.color9CD5FF>One Pace Premium</c></b>
Keep the project alive: <c.colora8c7fa>ko-fi.com/not6ip</c>

2
00:00:00.710 --> 00:00:03.370
Get moving right now, get moving right now

3
00:00:03.590 --> 00:00:06.460
Hoisting our flag high, we'll make it somehow

4
00:00:12.770 --> 00:00:15.500
Setting out all on our own to cross the endless sea,

5
00:00:15.500 --> 00:00:18.060
you know what we're searching for

6
00:00:18.860 --> 00:00:21.810
The worldwide enigma, treasures undiscovered

7
00:00:21.900 --> 00:00:23.940
Picking's ripe, so let's go explore

8
00:00:24.820 --> 00:00:27.960
We're all so excited, our hearts can't keep quiet

9
00:00:27.960 --> 00:00:29.710
Nothing left to do but press on

10
00:00:29.710 --> 00:00:35.590
Trailing after footprints left by the dreamers before us

11
00:00:36.420 --> 00:00:39.390
Stormy nights can try their best to sink us

12
00:00:39.390 --> 00:00:42.390
We'll sail on, if we just stick together

13
00:00:42.390 --> 00:00:46.540
Try and stop us if you can

14
00:00:46.680 --> 00:00:47.860
We always pull through

15
00:00:48.760 --> 00:00:51.590
Get moving right now, get moving right now

16
00:00:51.720 --> 00:00:54.550
Hoisting our flag high, we'll make it somehow

17
00:00:54.600 --> 00:00:57.140
Even if we sometimes shed tears,

18
00:00:57.230 --> 00:01:00.580
and want to hide them from prying eyes

19
00:01:00.770 --> 00:01:03.520
But go and chase it, yeah, go and chase it

20
00:01:03.690 --> 00:01:06.520
Run the direction the compass points in

21
00:01:06.610 --> 00:01:09.230
All our dreams are straight ahead it says

22
00:01:09.230 --> 00:01:11.400
So don't sit back, let's chase it

23
00:01:18.830 --> 00:01:21.490
Get moving right now, get moving right now

24
00:01:21.800 --> 00:01:24.540
We have to pull through ahead of them all

25
00:01:24.630 --> 00:01:27.120
If we hold firm and stand our ground,

26
00:01:27.220 --> 00:01:30.540
I know the future's within our grasp

27
00:01:30.600 --> 00:01:33.630
So go and chase it, yeah, go and chase it

28
00:01:33.680 --> 00:01:36.510
The world's our oyster, it's waiting for us

29
00:01:36.560 --> 00:01:38.930
All the sadness and the joy we see,

30
00:01:39.150 --> 00:01:41.430
let's etch it in our hearts

31
00:01:50.010 --> 00:01:53.430
<b>The Girl They Called a Devil</b>

32
00:01:54.050 --> 00:01:56.550
Despite Aqua Laguna, they've made it here.

33
00:01:56.550 --> 00:01:58.430
That's quite impressive, honestly.

34
00:01:59.310 --> 00:02:01.310
They're pretty lucky, sure.

35
00:02:01.310 --> 00:02:03.560
This time we have permission to kill them.

36
00:02:03.560 --> 00:02:06.610
If we don't need to hold back,
this'll be a cinch.

37
00:02:07.360 --> 00:02:08.480
The drawbridge?

38
00:02:08.480 --> 00:02:12.070
Yeah. The Franky Family is
working hard to lower it.

39
00:02:12.530 --> 00:02:16.660
The moment it lowers,
we're going to the other side.

40
00:02:16.660 --> 00:02:19.790
Really now... So close, yet so far.

41
00:02:29.750 --> 00:02:31.260
You...

42
00:02:31.260 --> 00:02:36.010
Really... just how big is
that burden she's lugging around?

43
00:02:37.390 --> 00:02:39.060
Hey, CP9!

44
00:02:39.060 --> 00:02:40.430
Listen up!

45
00:02:40.430 --> 00:02:44.060
You have my permission to kill them,
but do it here, in the tower!

46
00:02:45.770 --> 00:02:48.980
My life and my promotion
come first, no matter what!

47
00:02:49.610 --> 00:02:56.320
If I let them run wild, who will be there
to protect me when something goes wrong?

48
00:02:59.030 --> 00:03:00.830
You imbecilic pirates!

49
00:03:00.830 --> 00:03:06.290
You should recognize that acting brave
won't change a damn thing!

50
00:03:06.960 --> 00:03:11.300
You’re up against the power
of CP9’s assassins...

51
00:03:11.300 --> 00:03:16.180
and the weight of the immovable Gates of Justice!

52
00:03:16.180 --> 00:03:18.930
And lest we forget, I have the authority...

53
00:03:19.760 --> 00:03:25.600
to use this golden transponder
snail and exercise a buster call!

54
00:03:26.440 --> 00:03:28.020
A buster call!

55
00:03:28.020 --> 00:03:30.230
That's right.

56
00:03:30.230 --> 00:03:32.650
The same power...

57
00:03:33.110 --> 00:03:36.950
that wiped out your homeland
exactly twenty years ago, Nico Robin.

58
00:03:37.610 --> 00:03:42.950
As I recall, the name "Ohara" had
disappeared from the maps the following year!

59
00:03:43.370 --> 00:03:45.000
Robin's homeland?

60
00:03:45.620 --> 00:03:47.540
That masked bastard!

61
00:03:47.620 --> 00:03:52.710
I have nowhere to go
and no home to return to.

62
00:03:53.630 --> 00:03:54.710
Don't!

63
00:03:54.710 --> 00:03:56.130
Anything but that!

64
00:03:57.720 --> 00:04:00.680
What a reaction. I'm thrilled already!

65
00:04:01.220 --> 00:04:02.390
What?

66
00:04:02.390 --> 00:04:07.480
Does that mean you want me to press this button
to summon a buster call? Hm? How about it?

67
00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:13.940
You... Do you really understand
what happens when you press that button?

68
00:04:14.480 --> 00:04:16.400
Oh, I do.

69
00:04:16.400 --> 00:04:20.870
It'll eliminate any possibility
of the pirates leaving this island alive!

70
00:04:21.240 --> 00:04:23.330
With just the push of a button.

71
00:04:23.330 --> 00:04:25.410
It's very simple, really.

72
00:04:25.410 --> 00:04:27.620
It won't be that simple!

73
00:04:27.620 --> 00:04:31.080
Does this bring back some memories?

74
00:04:31.750 --> 00:04:34.840
I can try pressing it, if you'd like.

75
00:04:35.210 --> 00:04:37.050
Right here, right now?

76
00:04:41.430 --> 00:04:43.300
What're you doing?! Stop it!

77
00:04:45.930 --> 00:04:48.850
You still have the nerve
to talk back to me, huh?

78
00:05:06.120 --> 00:05:10.040
Like you said,
Ohara disappeared from the maps.

79
00:05:10.040 --> 00:05:13.130
But can you see human lives on a map?!

80
00:05:13.130 --> 00:05:16.960
The narrow way you people view the world...

81
00:05:17.420 --> 00:05:20.300
is exactly what allows for such a cruel act!

82
00:05:29.600 --> 00:05:34.020
The buster call is a merciless power
that disregards anything and everyone!

83
00:05:34.610 --> 00:05:37.190
You mustn't use it. Not that.

84
00:05:37.730 --> 00:05:39.110
Please!

85
00:05:39.110 --> 00:05:40.360
Anything but that!

86
00:05:44.070 --> 00:05:50.040
<b>Ohara
20 Years Ago – West Blue</b>

87
00:05:52.580 --> 00:05:54.000
Robin's over here!

88
00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:54.880
Get her!

89
00:05:54.920 --> 00:05:57.460
<b>Nico Robin (8 Years Old)</b>

90
00:05:57.460 --> 00:05:58.380
Ow!

91
00:05:59.460 --> 00:06:00.880
Bull's-eye!

92
00:06:00.880 --> 00:06:02.970
Hey, monster!

93
00:06:02.090 --> 00:06:03.970
Hey!

94
00:06:02.970 --> 00:06:03.970
You're creepy!

95
00:06:05.260 --> 00:06:10.270
– Monster! Monster! Monster! Monster!
– Monster! Monster! Monster! Monster!

96
00:06:14.440 --> 00:06:17.110
The monster hit me!

97
00:06:18.230 --> 00:06:19.860
She's creepy!

98
00:06:19.860 --> 00:06:21.570
We'll get you for this!

99
00:06:45.010 --> 00:06:46.010
Hey, you!

100
00:06:49.890 --> 00:06:54.310
My children came home crying,
saying you hit them for no reason.

101
00:06:54.810 --> 00:06:57.440
Stay away from my kids.

102
00:06:58.400 --> 00:07:00.400
Well, say something, will you?!

103
00:07:00.400 --> 00:07:02.070
What a pain...

104
00:07:02.070 --> 00:07:04.320
You really are a creepy child.

105
00:07:06.860 --> 00:07:07.820
Hey, wait!

106
00:07:07.820 --> 00:07:09.950
I'm not done with you yet!

107
00:07:18.170 --> 00:07:21.300
Mommy, what are we
having for dinner tonight?

108
00:07:21.300 --> 00:07:22.380
What would you like?

109
00:07:22.380 --> 00:07:24.670
What about...? Um...

110
00:07:24.670 --> 00:07:26.090
Rice omelet!

111
00:07:27.050 --> 00:07:29.050
You sure like rice omelets, don't you?

112
00:07:29.050 --> 00:07:29.800
Yep!

113
00:07:29.800 --> 00:07:32.520
We have to buy lots of eggs, then.

114
00:07:32.520 --> 00:07:33.850
All right!

115
00:07:42.320 --> 00:07:44.240
I'm back.

116
00:07:44.240 --> 00:07:46.570
Sorry I'm late.

117
00:07:47.450 --> 00:07:48.610
Aunt Roji?

118
00:07:59.670 --> 00:08:01.920
"Robin, today is..."

119
00:08:01.920 --> 00:08:03.960
...our daughter's birthday.

120
00:08:03.960 --> 00:08:08.840
So we decided that the three of us
would go out for dinner as a family.

121
00:08:09.390 --> 00:08:13.180
We left bread, so eat some for your dinner.

122
00:08:13.890 --> 00:08:16.810
Don't use too much jam.

123
00:08:17.350 --> 00:08:23.150
After dinner, but before we get home:
do the dishes, clean the house,

124
00:08:23.150 --> 00:08:28.820
take the laundry in,
and then go upstairs early.

125
00:08:35.870 --> 00:08:38.870
Mommy, what are we
having for dinner tonight?

126
00:08:38.870 --> 00:08:40.370
What would you like?

127
00:08:40.370 --> 00:08:43.040
What about...? Um...

128
00:08:43.040 --> 00:08:44.630
Rice omelet!

129
00:08:45.460 --> 00:08:47.380
You sure like rice omelets, don't you?

130
00:08:47.380 --> 00:08:48.090
Yep!

131
00:08:48.090 --> 00:08:50.470
We have to buy lots of eggs, then.

132
00:08:50.470 --> 00:08:52.890
All right!

133
00:09:05.860 --> 00:09:11.780
<b>The Tree of Knowledge
Ohara Library and Archaeological Research Center</b>

134
00:09:11.780 --> 00:09:13.660
Oh! There she is!

135
00:09:13.660 --> 00:09:14.950
Robin's almost here!

136
00:09:14.950 --> 00:09:16.950
Probably returning a book.

137
00:09:16.950 --> 00:09:18.700
Everyone, to your positions.

138
00:09:23.380 --> 00:09:27.710
Good evening, Professor Clover!
I came to return the book I borrowed.

139
00:09:31.840 --> 00:09:33.550
One, two...!

140
00:09:33.550 --> 00:09:36.060
Congratulations, Robin!

141
00:09:33.550 --> 00:09:37.260
– Congratulations, Robin!
– Congratulations, Robin!

142
00:09:33.590 --> 00:09:37.260
<b>The Archaeologists of Ohara</b>

143
00:09:37.770 --> 00:09:38.930
You're amazing, Robin!

144
00:09:38.930 --> 00:09:40.430
That's a genius for you!

145
00:09:40.430 --> 00:09:43.100
We got you a cake!

146
00:09:43.100 --> 00:09:46.360
Robin, the results are in for your doctoral exam!

147
00:09:46.360 --> 00:09:48.480
You achieved a perfect score!

148
00:09:48.480 --> 00:09:51.950
Henceforth, we acknowledge
you as an archaeologist!

149
00:09:52.530 --> 00:09:57.490
Now that you're one of us,
we will conduct research together.

150
00:09:58.830 --> 00:10:01.000
Here, this certifies that you're a scholar.

151
00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:02.670
Please accept it, Robin.

152
00:10:03.500 --> 00:10:05.130
I'm so proud of you, Robin.

153
00:10:05.130 --> 00:10:06.590
Congratulations!

154
00:10:08.250 --> 00:10:13.430
<b>Professor Clover (Authority on Archaeology)
Ohara Library's Head Librarian</b>

155
00:10:08.960 --> 00:10:13.430
Listen, Robin. You must develop a firm grasp of what it means to be an archaeologist.

156
00:10:13.760 --> 00:10:15.930
Yes, Professor Clover!

157
00:10:16.390 --> 00:10:20.140
Knowledge comes from the past!

158
00:10:20.140 --> 00:10:24.560
This Tree of Knowledge is 5,000 years old.

159
00:10:24.560 --> 00:10:30.190
For centuries, people have brought countless books
to this tree from all over the world.

160
00:10:30.610 --> 00:10:35.280
It's an irreplaceable treasure
for all of humanity!

161
00:10:35.660 --> 00:10:39.620
This is the world's largest, oldest library
and a glorious store of knowledge.

162
00:10:40.040 --> 00:10:45.370
Renowned archaeologists from across the seas
gather beneath this Tree of Knowledge.

163
00:10:45.750 --> 00:10:52.460
Indeed, thanks to these books,
we can unlock all the mysteries of the past!

164
00:10:53.300 --> 00:10:54.970
Got that, Robin?

165
00:10:54.970 --> 00:10:55.840
Yes!

166
00:10:56.840 --> 00:10:59.810
I'd like to see you researching
cultures around the world,

167
00:10:59.810 --> 00:11:03.390
contributing to human knowledge.

168
00:11:03.390 --> 00:11:07.770
Professor! I'd like to solve the mystery
behind the gap in history!

169
00:11:07.770 --> 00:11:08.650
Wha...?!

170
00:11:08.650 --> 00:11:09.980
No! You shouldn't!

171
00:11:09.980 --> 00:11:12.570
That is forbidden, and it always will be!

172
00:11:12.570 --> 00:11:14.530
What? Why?

173
00:11:14.530 --> 00:11:19.410
If we research the poneglyphs, we'll know
what happened during the Void Century, right?

174
00:11:20.990 --> 00:11:23.160
Why do you know that much?

175
00:11:23.160 --> 00:11:27.040
Did you peek into the basement
using your abilities?!

176
00:11:27.040 --> 00:11:27.920
But...

177
00:11:27.920 --> 00:11:32.840
You should know that trying to decipher
the poneglyphs is a criminal act!

178
00:11:32.840 --> 00:11:33.800
What...?

179
00:11:34.970 --> 00:11:36.090
But...

180
00:11:36.680 --> 00:11:38.970
in the basement, late into the night,

181
00:11:38.970 --> 00:11:41.220
everyone here researches the poneglyphs!

182
00:11:41.680 --> 00:11:44.890
Robin! How do you know that?!

183
00:11:45.430 --> 00:11:46.770
Explain yourself!

184
00:11:46.770 --> 00:11:49.610
Are you saying you saw that, too?

185
00:11:50.480 --> 00:11:52.070
Answer me, Robin!

186
00:11:53.440 --> 00:11:54.690
But...

187
00:11:55.900 --> 00:11:59.740
if I'd just walked up,
you wouldn't have let me in!

188
00:12:00.870 --> 00:12:02.410
I thought...

189
00:12:02.410 --> 00:12:07.960
you'd let me join in your research
if I became an archaeologist.

190
00:12:08.580 --> 00:12:10.580
So I studied very hard!

191
00:12:12.460 --> 00:12:13.880
Robin...

192
00:12:16.590 --> 00:12:22.550
It's true that you've acquired
enough knowledge to be called a scholar.

193
00:12:22.550 --> 00:12:25.640
But you're still a child.

194
00:12:25.640 --> 00:12:29.270
If word ever got out about our research,
our heads would roll.

195
00:12:29.270 --> 00:12:32.270
We're doing it fully aware of the risk.

196
00:12:32.270 --> 00:12:36.400
Ever since it became law 800 years ago,

197
00:12:36.400 --> 00:12:41.070
many scholars have lost their lives
in pursuit of forbidden knowledge.

198
00:12:41.490 --> 00:12:44.240
Now is as good as ever for you to hear this.

199
00:12:44.660 --> 00:12:48.580
The Ohara researchers
are the only ones in history

200
00:12:48.580 --> 00:12:51.460
who've managed to decipher the ancient texts.

201
00:12:52.290 --> 00:12:54.920
We cannot turn back.

202
00:12:55.300 --> 00:12:59.260
Swear to the Tree of Knowledge:
You will never go near the basement again!

203
00:12:59.970 --> 00:13:04.310
If you do, you will be barred entry
from both the lab and the library!

204
00:13:04.310 --> 00:13:05.470
Understood?

205
00:13:09.520 --> 00:13:10.600
Robin!

206
00:13:11.400 --> 00:13:15.190
She's following in her mother's
footsteps in every way.

207
00:13:15.190 --> 00:13:18.780
She still doesn't know
about the incident from the other day.

208
00:13:19.860 --> 00:13:23.740
Robin's mother, Olvia, has been captured.

209
00:13:24.200 --> 00:13:27.790
Her fate is already sealed.

210
00:13:28.500 --> 00:13:31.540
<b>The Following Day</b>

211
00:14:17.340 --> 00:14:19.420
W... W...

212
00:14:21.760 --> 00:14:23.220
Worms?

213
00:14:32.230 --> 00:14:34.310
That hit the spot!

214
00:14:38.270 --> 00:14:42.440
<b>Saul, a Castaway Giant</b>

215
00:14:42.490 --> 00:14:45.200
I’m alive!

216
00:14:45.660 --> 00:14:48.950
I wonder if she's okay, too.

217
00:14:50.700 --> 00:14:53.210
I'm safe for now.

218
00:14:53.210 --> 00:14:54.460
Thanks.

219
00:14:54.460 --> 00:14:57.330
Is there a town or something on this island?

220
00:14:57.330 --> 00:14:58.500
Yeah.

221
00:14:58.500 --> 00:15:00.300
I see.

222
00:15:02.010 --> 00:15:06.720
If I was going to wash up somewhere,
an uninhabited island would've been better.

223
00:15:14.310 --> 00:15:17.900
You can stay there if you want,
but nothing's gonna happen.

224
00:15:18.400 --> 00:15:23.570
I busted up my leg, so I've gotta stay put.

225
00:15:24.150 --> 00:15:29.030
I plan on eventually making a raft
and getting outta here.

226
00:15:30.580 --> 00:15:32.870
This your first time seeing a giant?

227
00:15:32.870 --> 00:15:34.000
Uh-huh.

228
00:15:34.620 --> 00:15:40.250
Then do me a favor and don't lump me in
with those guys from Elbaph.

229
00:15:40.250 --> 00:15:44.170
There are peaceful giant folk too.

230
00:15:47.090 --> 00:15:50.470
I know it's a long shot, but I'll ask you anyway.

231
00:15:50.470 --> 00:15:55.930
When you get home, I'd appreciate it
if you kept quiet about me.

232
00:15:56.350 --> 00:15:57.690
Okay.

233
00:15:58.600 --> 00:16:00.360
That was too easy.

234
00:16:00.360 --> 00:16:02.230
She'll definitely tell.

235
00:16:02.690 --> 00:16:04.190
I won't tell.

236
00:16:08.200 --> 00:16:09.740
I'd like to believe you!

237
00:16:09.740 --> 00:16:13.290
There's just no way a child can keep a secret.

238
00:16:13.910 --> 00:16:17.410
I won't tell because
I'm not interested in you.

239
00:16:33.260 --> 00:16:34.770
"Dereshi"?

240
00:16:34.770 --> 00:16:36.180
What does that mean?

241
00:16:36.770 --> 00:16:39.770
What does it mean? I'm just laughing.

242
00:16:42.400 --> 00:16:43.860
You're laughing?

243
00:16:44.270 --> 00:16:46.860
You're a funny girl!

244
00:16:51.490 --> 00:16:52.700
What a weird laugh!

245
00:16:56.200 --> 00:17:00.830
People have always told me
I'm no good at laughing.

246
00:17:00.830 --> 00:17:03.840
You've got a cute laugh, though.

247
00:17:03.840 --> 00:17:04.460
What?

248
00:17:04.460 --> 00:17:06.670
You should laugh more!

249
00:17:09.260 --> 00:17:11.970
My name is Saul.

250
00:17:11.970 --> 00:17:14.220
Jaguar D. Saul.

251
00:17:15.140 --> 00:17:16.220
"D"?

252
00:17:16.220 --> 00:17:17.430
Yeah.

253
00:17:17.430 --> 00:17:23.440
I don't know why, but everyone
in my family has it in their names.

254
00:17:23.440 --> 00:17:24.690
What's your name?

255
00:17:25.190 --> 00:17:26.190
Robin.

256
00:17:26.190 --> 00:17:31.700
To tell you the truth, Robin,
people are after me.

257
00:17:31.700 --> 00:17:34.240
I'll be in big trouble if I'm spotted.

258
00:17:34.240 --> 00:17:36.580
I said I won't tell!

259
00:17:37.660 --> 00:17:41.160
<b>Three Days After the Giant Drifted Ashore</b>

260
00:17:47.300 --> 00:17:48.960
That was delicious!

261
00:17:48.960 --> 00:17:50.470
Here's another one.

262
00:17:53.590 --> 00:17:56.850
I appreciate the thought,
but you go ahead and eat it.

263
00:17:57.680 --> 00:17:59.600
I’m not hungry.

264
00:18:00.140 --> 00:18:02.810
I caught and ate some fish last night.

265
00:18:04.400 --> 00:18:05.560
Okay.

266
00:18:05.560 --> 00:18:08.780
Well, I'll keep working on my raft.

267
00:18:08.780 --> 00:18:11.030
It'll be completed soon.

268
00:18:16.280 --> 00:18:20.080
In any case, you've sure got
lots of time on your hands, huh?

269
00:18:20.080 --> 00:18:24.080
You've been with me nonstop
for the past several days.

270
00:18:24.080 --> 00:18:26.210
You'll worry your parents and friends.

271
00:18:28.590 --> 00:18:29.880
I don't have parents.

272
00:18:30.510 --> 00:18:34.800
Well, I do have a mother, but she's been
working far away since I was little.

273
00:18:34.800 --> 00:18:36.350
I don't even remember her face.

274
00:18:37.220 --> 00:18:43.230
I like the archaeologists here, but they keep me
away from their research, so I feel left out.

275
00:18:43.690 --> 00:18:48.360
Kids in town say that I'm creepy,
so I don't want to play with them.

276
00:18:50.860 --> 00:18:54.360
Oh, so you've eaten a devil fruit, huh?

277
00:18:55.110 --> 00:18:56.450
You aren't scared?

278
00:18:56.450 --> 00:19:02.750
I've traveled the Grand Line,
so I've seen tons of powerful devil fruits.

279
00:19:03.660 --> 00:19:05.370
I see...

280
00:19:05.370 --> 00:19:06.750
I envy you.

281
00:19:07.210 --> 00:19:08.960
That looks convenient!

282
00:19:16.590 --> 00:19:18.100
Your laugh really is weird.

283
00:19:19.600 --> 00:19:22.310
Weird or not...

284
00:19:22.310 --> 00:19:23.600
you know...

285
00:19:23.600 --> 00:19:27.310
if you laugh, it'll make you happy!

286
00:19:27.810 --> 00:19:28.860
Why?

287
00:19:28.860 --> 00:19:32.980
"Why?" When you're having fun, you laugh.

288
00:19:32.980 --> 00:19:37.410
So if you laugh, you'll have fun.

289
00:19:37.780 --> 00:19:41.740
Although you're only a child,
you seem to be going through hard times.

290
00:19:41.740 --> 00:19:43.160
So laugh.

291
00:19:43.160 --> 00:19:45.500
When the pain gets
to be too much, just laugh.

292
00:19:46.160 --> 00:19:48.380
It seems dumb to laugh
when you're in pain.

293
00:19:48.380 --> 00:19:50.170
That's not true.

294
00:19:51.550 --> 00:19:52.800
Go ahead!

295
00:19:52.800 --> 00:19:55.720
Give it your best shot!

296
00:20:02.760 --> 00:20:04.390
That's right!

297
00:20:04.390 --> 00:20:06.230
Do it like this!

298
00:20:14.480 --> 00:20:16.280
That's good! That's good!

299
00:20:21.700 --> 00:20:23.450
This is Marine Headquarters.

300
00:20:23.450 --> 00:20:25.700
Chief Spandine, please come in.

301
00:20:26.080 --> 00:20:27.960
They want to talk to you, Chief.

302
00:20:27.960 --> 00:20:31.130
Ignore it. I'm sure they
just want a status report.

303
00:20:31.170 --> 00:20:34.710
<b>Somewhere in the West Blue</b>

304
00:20:31.630 --> 00:20:34.710
We'll contact them when we see the shore.

305
00:20:34.760 --> 00:20:41.890
<b>Spandine, CP9 Chief
(20 Years Ago)</b>

306
00:20:35.380 --> 00:20:37.880
I don't care whether it's Ohara or Opera,

307
00:20:37.880 --> 00:20:41.890
why do I have to come
all the way to the West Blue?

308
00:20:42.350 --> 00:20:44.100
Seriously.

309
00:20:44.100 --> 00:20:46.350
What a worthless mission.

310
00:20:47.390 --> 00:20:52.150
<b>The Following Day, Four Days After the Giant Drifted Ashore</b>

311
00:21:06.410 --> 00:21:09.120
Hey, is it true that a Marine ship is here?

312
00:21:09.120 --> 00:21:10.920
What? A Marine ship?

313
00:21:10.920 --> 00:21:13.630
Yeah, I heard it was found
anchored here at dawn.

314
00:21:13.630 --> 00:21:15.550
Why would the Marines come...

315
00:21:15.550 --> 00:21:17.260
...to such a remote island?

316
00:21:17.260 --> 00:21:21.130
But there are no Marines in sight.

317
00:21:21.130 --> 00:21:22.260
What the heck?

318
00:21:22.590 --> 00:21:25.850
No one's on it. It's like a ghost ship.

319
00:21:25.850 --> 00:21:27.970
That's ridiculous.

320
00:21:28.680 --> 00:21:29.600
Professor!

321
00:21:29.600 --> 00:21:31.390
Professor Clover!

322
00:21:34.610 --> 00:21:35.980
Did something happen?

323
00:21:36.570 --> 00:21:41.240
I don't believe it, but a Marine ship
is anchored at the shore!

324
00:21:41.240 --> 00:21:44.450
It's likely an investigation.
We should be extra cautious!

325
00:21:46.030 --> 00:21:47.740
Inform all the scholars.

326
00:21:50.910 --> 00:21:53.540
And the raft's done!

327
00:21:59.050 --> 00:22:01.090
Then... you're leaving already?

328
00:22:01.090 --> 00:22:02.970
What's wrong?

329
00:22:02.970 --> 00:22:06.430
You've got "I'll be lonely"
written all over your face.

330
00:22:07.470 --> 00:22:11.230
Come to think of it, I was considering
putting a flag or something on it.

331
00:22:11.230 --> 00:22:13.730
So I'll stay here a little longer.

332
00:22:20.940 --> 00:22:22.400
To sea...?

333
00:22:22.400 --> 00:22:25.030
So you wanna leave the island too?

334
00:22:25.030 --> 00:22:25.910
Yep.

335
00:22:26.780 --> 00:22:30.870
My mother has been busy with her
archaeological research all this time.

336
00:22:31.710 --> 00:22:34.210
But the next time she
comes back to the island,

337
00:22:34.540 --> 00:22:37.170
I'm going to ask her
to take me with her to sea.

338
00:22:37.500 --> 00:22:42.130
That's why I studied so hard and was finally
able to become an archaeologist.

339
00:22:42.130 --> 00:22:44.010
An archaeologist?

340
00:22:44.010 --> 00:22:45.970
When you're still a young'un?

341
00:22:46.430 --> 00:22:47.350
Yep.

342
00:22:47.930 --> 00:22:49.260
But...

343
00:22:49.260 --> 00:22:53.810
you don't even remember
your mother's face, right?

344
00:22:53.810 --> 00:22:56.270
Right... but she's still my mother.

345
00:22:57.360 --> 00:22:58.690
I wanna see her.

346
00:23:01.610 --> 00:23:03.190
Say, Saul...

347
00:23:03.570 --> 00:23:08.200
Did you know that history has a big gap
of 100 years that no one knows about?

348
00:23:08.200 --> 00:23:12.410
Yeah. It's called the Void Century.

349
00:23:12.410 --> 00:23:16.960
I'm curious about it, but the government
prohibits people from investigating, so...

350
00:23:17.290 --> 00:23:22.550
Yeah. I heard that my mother is
traveling around the world investigating it.

351
00:23:22.550 --> 00:23:26.430
But don't tell anyone about it,
since it's actually a crime.

352
00:23:26.430 --> 00:23:27.300
What?!

353
00:23:27.760 --> 00:23:33.180
C-Could that mean that she's traveling
in search of those stones called poneglyphs?

354
00:23:34.100 --> 00:23:35.810
You know about the poneglyphs?

355
00:23:35.810 --> 00:23:37.310
Of course I do!

356
00:23:37.310 --> 00:23:41.780
But don't mention them
in front of other people, okay?!

357
00:23:42.150 --> 00:23:45.280
Not to mention, about your
mother traveling in search of–

358
00:23:48.490 --> 00:23:49.620
What's wrong?

359
00:23:49.990 --> 00:23:54.040
Robin... do you know your mother's name?

360
00:23:54.580 --> 00:23:55.540
Olvia.

361
00:23:57.540 --> 00:23:59.500
It's Nico Olvia.

362
00:24:06.680 --> 00:24:07.880
Saul?!

363
00:24:08.260 --> 00:24:11.850
Robin... is Olvia's daughter!

364
00:24:12.180 --> 00:24:14.810
Then... could this place be...

365
00:24:15.180 --> 00:24:17.560
an island called Ohara?!

366
00:24:17.560 --> 00:24:18.310
Yeah.

367
00:24:19.560 --> 00:24:21.860
This is terrible! Oh, no!

368
00:24:21.860 --> 00:24:26.150
I actually drifted to Ohara?!

369
00:24:26.610 --> 00:24:28.570
There's no time to chat!

370
00:24:28.990 --> 00:24:29.700
Robin!

371
00:24:29.700 --> 00:24:30.410
What is it?

372
00:24:30.410 --> 00:24:34.450
This might come as a shock,
but I need you to listen carefully!

373
00:24:34.450 --> 00:24:38.790
Marine battleships should be
headed to Ohara right now.

374
00:24:39.290 --> 00:24:41.210
The Marines? Why?

375
00:24:41.210 --> 00:24:44.130
In order to eliminate
the scholars on this island!

376
00:24:45.710 --> 00:24:47.300
Eliminate them?

377
00:24:48.470 --> 00:24:51.340
Don't tell the...

378
00:24:50.510 --> 00:24:51.720
That's a lie...

379
00:24:51.340 --> 00:24:54.100
Don't tell the government you're a scholar!

380
00:24:53.640 --> 00:24:54.930
That's a lie...!

381
00:24:54.100 --> 00:24:55.970
Got that?!

382
00:24:56.310 --> 00:24:57.680
That's a lie!

383
00:24:57.680 --> 00:24:59.060
It's true!

384
00:24:59.060 --> 00:25:01.150
I'd never lie to you!

385
00:25:01.150 --> 00:25:04.320
Go to town right now to see
if anything strange is happening!

386
00:25:04.320 --> 00:25:07.690
It's possible your mother came back, too!

387
00:25:07.690 --> 00:25:08.530
What?!

388
00:25:16.490 --> 00:25:19.040
<b>Nico Olvia
Archaeologist</b>

389
00:25:16.830 --> 00:25:19.040
It's been a while, everyone.

390
00:25:19.040 --> 00:25:20.040
Olvia...

391
00:25:20.040 --> 00:25:21.040
Olvia...!

392
00:25:21.040 --> 00:25:23.420
So you were the one on that Marine ship!

393
00:25:23.420 --> 00:25:25.050
We thought they'd captured you!

394
00:25:32.840 --> 00:25:36.220
I'm sorry that bad news
accompanied my return.

395
00:25:36.220 --> 00:25:37.930
But what I just said is true.

396
00:25:37.930 --> 00:25:42.150
Meaning the government has finally
set its sights on Ohara?

397
00:25:42.810 --> 00:25:44.560
Did you hear the news?

398
00:25:44.560 --> 00:25:49.440
The poneglyph search team that set off
from Ohara six years ago was annihilated.

399
00:25:49.440 --> 00:25:51.200
All of them except for me...

400
00:25:51.200 --> 00:25:54.320
A total of thirty-three members...

401
00:25:54.320 --> 00:25:56.830
I was also temporarily captured.

402
00:25:56.830 --> 00:26:01.500
The government carefully analyzed
my murdered companions’ belongings

403
00:26:01.500 --> 00:26:04.500
and discovered that we came from Ohara.

404
00:26:05.710 --> 00:26:07.380
I have no excuse!

405
00:26:07.380 --> 00:26:10.670
Everyone on this island is in danger
because of our actions!

406
00:26:10.670 --> 00:26:14.390
Stop it! It's no one's fault!

407
00:26:14.390 --> 00:26:18.640
Those who set out to sea and those
who stayed here—we're all one team!

408
00:26:18.640 --> 00:26:21.940
You were the ones truly suffering.

409
00:26:22.940 --> 00:26:24.650
You've been through hell.

410
00:26:26.230 --> 00:26:27.610
Professor...

411
00:26:27.980 --> 00:26:31.950
Talented scholars from around the world

412
00:26:31.950 --> 00:26:34.860
gather in Ohara to pursue history,

413
00:26:34.860 --> 00:26:37.740
and the government has
always considered us a threat.

414
00:26:38.240 --> 00:26:41.330
They must think they finally
have something on us.

415
00:26:41.330 --> 00:26:43.670
They won't pass up such an opportunity.

416
00:26:43.670 --> 00:26:48.000
Yes, but we found out before it was too late!

417
00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:52.340
Ultimately, they will eliminate
all known scholars in Ohara!

418
00:26:52.720 --> 00:26:56.090
So, everyone, we must
escape Ohara immediately!

419
00:26:56.090 --> 00:26:58.100
You're right.

420
00:26:58.100 --> 00:27:03.060
Unfortunately, I don't think we'll be able
to slip past their investigation like usual...

421
00:27:03.430 --> 00:27:07.150
especially if they plan to kill us.

422
00:27:07.150 --> 00:27:08.480
Then, hurry up and–

423
00:27:08.860 --> 00:27:10.480
But you know, Olvia,

424
00:27:11.030 --> 00:27:15.280
I can't just run and leave behind
this treasure of humanity.

425
00:27:15.280 --> 00:27:16.780
You should know that.

426
00:27:16.780 --> 00:27:19.030
We feel the same way, Olvia.

427
00:27:20.160 --> 00:27:21.580
You guys...

428
00:27:21.580 --> 00:27:24.330
We don't know what the government is up to.

429
00:27:24.330 --> 00:27:28.080
But escaping means our precious history
will no longer be protected.

430
00:27:28.420 --> 00:27:30.920
We'll try whatever we can,
just like we always have.

431
00:27:30.920 --> 00:27:32.840
More importantly...

432
00:27:33.170 --> 00:27:35.800
there's surely one more thing
weighing on you.

433
00:27:36.760 --> 00:27:39.010
But... I can't see her.

434
00:27:39.970 --> 00:27:41.720
Make up your mind, Olvia!

435
00:27:41.720 --> 00:27:43.980
Are you gonna come aboard the ship or not?

436
00:27:43.980 --> 00:27:46.560
Stay if you're gonna regret leaving your child!

437
00:27:46.560 --> 00:27:48.690
We'll fulfill your husband's dream, so–

438
00:27:49.560 --> 00:27:51.190
No! I'll come with you!

439
00:27:51.190 --> 00:27:53.570
I'm a scholar of Ohara.

440
00:27:53.570 --> 00:27:56.860
I can't abandon the will of our forebears!

441
00:27:57.820 --> 00:27:59.240
I'm sorry, Robin.

442
00:27:59.240 --> 00:28:02.990
I'll be home once we've solved every mystery!

443
00:28:09.250 --> 00:28:10.920
Mommy...

444
00:28:10.920 --> 00:28:13.590
Where's Mommy? Where did Mommy go?

445
00:28:13.590 --> 00:28:16.090
Your mother set out to sea for work.

446
00:28:16.090 --> 00:28:18.760
You'll stay here with us for a while.

447
00:28:18.760 --> 00:28:21.720
You're noisy! Be quiet or I'll hit you!

448
00:28:21.720 --> 00:28:23.810
Hey, stop it. She's only two.

449
00:28:23.810 --> 00:28:25.730
Our daughter is also two.

450
00:28:25.730 --> 00:28:28.270
I don't care that she's your sister's child.

451
00:28:28.270 --> 00:28:31.400
How dare you impose
such a burden on us!

452
00:28:34.650 --> 00:28:35.820
Who's there?!

453
00:28:35.820 --> 00:28:37.570
Don't move!

454
00:28:39.360 --> 00:28:42.280
U-Um... I... Um...

455
00:28:45.660 --> 00:28:46.910
I'm sorry!

456
00:28:49.080 --> 00:28:52.540
When you wanna read books,
just let me know.

457
00:28:52.540 --> 00:28:55.510
But I don't have any money...

458
00:28:55.880 --> 00:28:57.630
You don't have to pay.

459
00:28:57.630 --> 00:29:00.130
You can read them all for free.

460
00:29:00.130 --> 00:29:00.760
Free?

461
00:29:00.760 --> 00:29:04.260
Yeah, since this is
the greatest library in the world.

462
00:29:04.260 --> 00:29:05.390
The greatest?

463
00:29:05.390 --> 00:29:06.640
That's right.

464
00:29:06.640 --> 00:29:09.480
By the way, you're
Olvia's daughter, aren't you?

465
00:29:10.480 --> 00:29:11.940
Do you like books?

466
00:29:14.940 --> 00:29:18.320
She looks just like you did
when you were a child.

467
00:29:18.320 --> 00:29:20.910
And just like you at that age,
she's a prodigy.

468
00:29:22.030 --> 00:29:24.240
So long as I know she's okay...

469
00:29:25.740 --> 00:29:29.040
I'm too far down this path,
so I must sever ties.

470
00:29:29.580 --> 00:29:32.960
I can't let her become known
as a criminal's daughter.

471
00:29:32.960 --> 00:29:36.710
Professor Clover! This time, there's a ship
flying a World Government flag!

472
00:29:37.170 --> 00:29:41.050
A government ship has come
all the way to the West Blue?

473
00:29:41.050 --> 00:29:44.600
This seems quite serious, indeed.

474
00:29:46.930 --> 00:29:48.430
Everyone, listen.

475
00:29:48.430 --> 00:29:51.560
We are neither fellow scholars
nor acquaintances.

476
00:29:54.020 --> 00:29:57.230
Keep that in mind, no matter what happens!

477
00:29:57.230 --> 00:30:00.150
Wait, Olvia! What are you going to do?!

478
00:30:00.150 --> 00:30:03.410
Hey, notify headquarters
that we've reached our destination.

479
00:30:00.190 --> 00:30:04.160
<b>Ohara Coastline</b>

480
00:30:04.990 --> 00:30:07.120
Now, go, go, go! Keep it moving!

481
00:30:07.660 --> 00:30:10.080
My goodness... What a pain.

482
00:30:11.330 --> 00:30:14.460
In any case, this work had
better get me a promotion.

483
00:30:14.460 --> 00:30:18.460
Hey, go get all the scholars
and restrain them.

484
00:30:18.460 --> 00:30:19.050
– Yes, sir!
– Yes, sir!

485
00:30:19.800 --> 00:30:20.920
What's going on?!

486
00:30:20.920 --> 00:30:23.510
A woman with a gun is running around!

487
00:30:41.860 --> 00:30:43.740
How terrible!

488
00:30:43.740 --> 00:30:46.700
I'm sorry, Robin!

489
00:30:46.700 --> 00:30:47.870
Vice Admiral Kuzan!

490
00:30:46.740 --> 00:30:50.120
<b>Somewhere in the West Blue</b>

491
00:30:47.870 --> 00:30:49.950
Huh...? What is it?

492
00:30:49.950 --> 00:30:53.660
It seems Chief Spandine of CP9
has arrived in Ohara.

493
00:30:53.660 --> 00:30:55.790
What...?

494
00:30:55.790 --> 00:30:57.540
Is that something so important

495
00:30:57.540 --> 00:30:59.550
that you had to wake me up to tell me?!

496
00:30:57.590 --> 00:31:01.050
<b>Vice Admiral Kuzan, Marine Headquarters
(Later to Become Admiral Aokiji)</b>

497
00:30:59.550 --> 00:31:01.050
I-I'm sorry!

498
00:31:06.680 --> 00:31:13.220
I know there’s something that I need to say,

499
00:31:13.600 --> 00:31:17.190
but I can’t seem to find the words

500
00:31:17.440 --> 00:31:25.070
Wandering aimlessly, forever on the hunt, that’s how I’ve lived

501
00:31:25.070 --> 00:31:30.830
And now there’s something right in front of me,

502
00:31:32.030 --> 00:31:35.540
a light that shines brighter than gold

503
00:31:35.910 --> 00:31:40.920
But as I trail behind, it speeds out of sight.

504
00:31:40.920 --> 00:31:47.510
What’s going on? Scared of what’s yet to come

505
00:31:47.840 --> 00:31:53.760
So many times, so many times as we both stumbled on the way

506
00:31:53.970 --> 00:31:56.770
We’ve had our highs, we’ve had our lows;

507
00:31:57.060 --> 00:31:59.850
Yeah, we just take it day by day

508
00:32:00.150 --> 00:32:06.400
Never forget that even when the night snuffs out the light

509
00:32:06.690 --> 00:32:13.030
When the dark has passed the sun will rise again
